author: emlivingherbestlife
body: üåøSpring is the perfect time to start thinking about which of your houseplants may need to be repotted. . ü™¥So here are some signs that your plant has outgrown its pot üëáüèΩ . 1Ô∏è‚É£ Roots poking out of the drainage holes at the bottom of the pot. . 2Ô∏è‚É£ Roots poking up out of the top soil and pot. . 3Ô∏è‚É£ The pot appears to be bulging and has taken on an oval form, rather than the circular shape it started off as. . 4Ô∏è‚É£ The plants roots are ‚Äúrootbound‚Äù i.e they‚Äôre growing around and around, in a circular fashion. . üçÄNow let me be clear. YOU DO NOT HAVE TO REPOT YOUR HOUSEPLANTS. In general they‚Äôre much more tolerant of being a little rootbound than people often think. I know that many indoor gardeners do not have the time or desire to repot and that‚Äôs ok. Contrary to what is popular spouted, unless the plant is extremely rootbound, most of our houseplants will be just fine for several years in the same pot. They may not reach their potential in terms of growth, but they can be perfectly healthy, especially if you take other steps to care for them. Such as ensuring they get enough light, that they aren‚Äôt over/under waters and that you fertilise them appropriately.  . üå±That being said many of us do want to repot our houseplants. With one of the reasons being that we want to support our plants to put on as much growth as possible and to develop in maturity.  . ü™¥I will be covering how to repot your houseplants in my next video!  . #plantcare #planttok #repotting #houseplanttips #planttips #indoorgarden #urbanjungle

author: tannertheplanter
body: Self watering pots in and of themselves aren‚Äôt bad, and are completely fine for your plant. The problem is with how misleading the marketing is. You‚Äôre supposed to use them as you would any potted plant and only water when the plant needs watered. Then, you dump water in the reservoir and it sucks it up from the bottom. Self watering pots are just fancier, more expensive cache pots. However, the marketers of these products would have you think that water should always be kept in the reservoir and the plant will just drink what it needs which is completely false! What a shame‚Ä¶. #planttiktok #planttips #houseplants

author: tannertheplanter
body: This is called Kokedama- a traditional Japanese style of keeping plants. For this process I like to remove as much soil as I can, then use peat moss to form a ball around the roots. I then use sheet moss as a decorative layer around the plants root ball and bind it with string. We replace this moss every 1-2 years, or as needed. We water this plant by soaking the root ball. Not all plants do well in this setup, but most houseplants do! #planttips #plantsoftiktok

author: emlivingherbestlife
body: üåøKnowing when to water your houseplants is, in my opinion, the number 1 aspect of plant care that you want to master. . ü™¥Don‚Äôt get me wrong, it is not an exact science, and we can all do it in our own way! BUT there are some basic principles, that we can all agree on. Grasp these, and it will ensure that your plants don‚Äôt die from the leading cause of plant death ü™¥‚ò†Ô∏è- OVERWATERING üí¶üí¶üí¶ . üå±So first things first, overwatering is NOT about how much water we give our plants. It‚Äôs about how often we water them‚Ä¶but not how often in terms of time. Rather, it‚Äôs about the state of the soil, and simply put - how wet it is. . If you think about it - in a warm home your plants soil will dry out quickly. Whilst,  in a cooler environment it will take much longer for the soil to dry out. And as the seasons progress our home environments change.  So we can‚Äôt just reply on a watering schedule, being able to assess the state of the soil is key.  . üí°To assess- Just remember, moist soil will stick to your finger or a chopstick‚Ä¶and if all else fails - get yourself a moisture meter üí¶üå± . üå± So why is it important that we let the soil dry out at least partially between waterings? Well, if the soil is permanently wet and saturated, then air CANNOT circulate around the roots. . ü™¥Without air (oxygen) circulating, microbial imbalance occurs, the roots start to rot, and overtime the plant will die.  . üåøYou‚Äôll notice YELLOW LEAVES, MUSHY foul SMELLING roots, LEAVES DROPPING , and eventually plant death.  .  üå±The key to avoiding this is assessing the soil and letting it BREATHE between waterings‚Ä¶by this I mean letting the soil DRY OUT partially/completely between waterings. THATS THE KEY üóù . My personal targets are: 1Ô∏è‚É£. If it‚Äôs a succulent I aim to let the soil dry out 100% between watering. 2Ô∏è‚É£. For most other houseplants (bar a few exceptions) I aim to have the soil dry out around 75% between waterings . #plantcare #planttips #houseplants #houseplantcare #indoorgarden #howtokeepplantsalive

author: tannertheplanter
body: This houseplant is likely the most popular anthurium of all time- largely due to its easy care and magnificent blooms. I‚Äôve transferred this one to water culture, or, hydroponics- even easier! I love the roots on this plant, which is one reason I chose to go this route. To make the transition I simply bare root the plant- meaning take all the soil off! Once the roots are clean I add a root inoculant- that‚Äôll help keep the roots clean and harmful bacteria levels low. This step isn‚Äôt necessary but definitely helps! From here I rinse the roots daily until I see absolutely no soil left behind. Water changes are every 7 days after that, using distilled or reverse osmosis water. I also add a bit of hydroponic fertilizer to keep this baby happy. Of course, like always, light is most important! Make sure to give this plant super bright light to maintain flowering. #anthurium #houseplants

body: Replying to @lizjustiniano Water-loving houseplants FTW! üåøüí¶ If you're looking for easy-to-grow plants that can thrive in water forever, look no further than these beauties. Chinese evergreen, Monstera, Pothos, Lucky Bamboo, Spider plant, and Philodendrons are all great options for beginners and experienced plant parents alike. Not only are they low maintenance, but they also purify the air and add a touch of green to your indoor space. With proper care and attention, these houseplants can grow and thrive in water for years to come. Just make sure to change the water regularly and feed them with a good water soluble fertilizer. body: Pot material and drainage plays a huge part in how much room for error you get with your houseplants.
